<paper id="1584746212"><title>A successful attack against the DES</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="Isfahan University Of Technology" id="292299592">Faramarz Hendessi</author><author org="Isfahan University Of Technology" id="2163026430">Mohammad R. Aref</author></authors><n_citation>2</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1503267625</reference><reference>1991374982</reference></references><venue id="1129078273" type="C">Information Theory and Applications</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-57936-2_32</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.60203">Watermarking attack</keyword><keyword weight="0.51984">Multiple encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.55369">Brute-force attack</keyword><keyword weight="0.40679">Mathematical optimization</keyword><keyword weight="0.43669">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.54914">Advanced Encryption Standard</keyword><keyword weight="0.42448">Computer network</keyword><keyword weight="0.53016">Encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.56187">40-bit encryption</keyword><keyword weight="0.5543">Triple DES</keyword><keyword weight="0.43339">Computer engineering</keyword><keyword weight="0.53851">56-bit encryption</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>It is shown that the Data Encryption Standard (DES) function is divided into 68 subfunctions, and therefore the exhaustive key search attack could be done by a pipelining method. A chip is designed whose purpose is to attack the DES and a searching machine is detailed based on it. It is shown that the DES could be broken, easily and cheaply, by this machine.</abstract></paper>